        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>structured citation</strong> is a formal listing of your business's name, address, and phone number (NAP) on a directory, data aggregator, or review platform — such as Yelp, Apple Maps, or a chamber of commerce site. Because the data appears in fixed, machine-readable fields, Google can parse and cross-reference it to verify your business's legitimacy and location, directly influencing local map pack rankings.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Directory Listings, NAP Listings</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If you run a local business, structured citations are one of the most reliable levers you have over your local pack ranking. Get them right — consistent, complete, and on authoritative sources — and you send a steady stream of trust signals to Google that your business is real, established, and deserving of visibility.</p>

        <h2 id="what-are">What are structured citations?</h2>
        <p>A structured citation is any online mention of your business that appears within a defined, formatted template — specifically one that separates your name, address, and phone number into distinct fields. This is in contrast to an unstructured citation, where your business details appear embedded within editorial prose.</p>
        <p>Classic structured citation sources include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>General directories:</strong> Yelp, Apple Maps, Bing Places, Facebook, Foursquare</li>
          <li><strong>Data aggregators:</strong> Data Axle (formerly InfoUSA), Localeze, Foursquare (as aggregator), Acxiom</li>
          <li><strong>Industry-specific directories:</strong> Healthgrades (healthcare), Avvo (legal), Houzz (home services), TripAdvisor (hospitality)</li>
          <li><strong>Local directories:</strong> Chamber of commerce sites, city business directories, local newspaper business listings</li>
        </ul>
        <p>What distinguishes all of these is a templated page structure with defined slots for each piece of NAP data — rather than a journalist simply mentioning your address in a sentence.</p>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why structured citations matter for local SEO</h2>
        <p>Local search algorithms rely on cross-referencing business data across the web to determine relevance and trustworthiness. When Google's crawlers find your business name, address, and phone number listed consistently across dozens of authoritative sources, it strengthens the signal that your business is legitimate and accurately located.</p>
        <p>Citation signals — specifically volume, accuracy, and consistency — rank among the top local pack ranking factors in every major local SEO study, including the Local Search Ranking Factors survey and BrightLocal's annual research. Three mechanisms drive this:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Verification.</strong> Google can't visit your physical location. Citations are how it corroborates the details in your Google Business Profile. Consistent NAP across trusted directories reduces doubt and boosts your prominence score.</li>
          <li><strong>Discovery.</strong> Data aggregators feed their data into smaller downstream directories, GPS devices, voice assistants, and in-car navigation systems. A citation with an aggregator like Data Axle can multiply into dozens of downstream placements automatically.</li>
          <li><strong>Authority distribution.</strong> High-DA directories that list your business pass a small amount of link authority to your site if they include a backlink. Even without a link, the mention itself contributes to your overall citation footprint.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="structured-vs-unstructured">Structured vs unstructured citations</h2>
        <p>Both citation types matter for local SEO, but they serve different functions. Understanding the distinction helps you prioritise your efforts.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Attribute</th><th>Structured Citation</th><th>Unstructured Citation</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Format</strong></td>
                <td>Fixed template fields (name, address, phone)</td>
                <td>NAP embedded in editorial prose</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Source examples</strong></td><td>Yelp, Apple Maps, Yellow Pages</td><td>Blog posts, news articles, podcast show notes</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Machine readability</strong></td><td>High — easily parsed by crawlers</td><td>Lower — requires NLP extraction</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Scalability</strong></td><td>High — aggregators distribute at scale</td><td>Low — each mention is one-off editorial</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Local ranking impact</strong></td><td>Strong — direct verification signal</td><td>Moderate — adds credibility and context</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>The practical takeaway: build structured citations first to establish your baseline NAP verification. Then pursue unstructured citations (via digital PR, content partnerships, and local news coverage) to add topical authority and link equity on top.</p>

        <h2 id="nap-consistency">NAP consistency — the golden rule</h2>
        <p>The entire value of structured citations depends on consistent NAP data. Even small variations in your business name, address format, or phone number confuse Google's entity resolution and dilute the signal your citations produce.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">High-risk inconsistencies</div>
          <p>These variations look minor to humans but create separate entity signals for Google: "St." vs "Street", "Suite 4" vs "Ste 4" vs "#4", "LLC" in some listings but not others, a local number in some places and an 800 number in others. Standardise every field before you start building.</p>
        </div>

        <p>Before building any new citations, decide on your canonical NAP format and document it. Then audit every existing listing and bring each one into conformance. The order of operations matters — fix inconsistencies before adding volume.</p>

        <h2 id="tier-structure">The three-tier citation structure</h2>
        <p>Not all citation sources carry equal weight. Local SEO practitioners typically organise citation building into three tiers based on authority and data influence:</p>

        <h3>Tier 1 — Data aggregators</h3>
        <p>These are the root sources from which hundreds of downstream directories pull business data. Correct listings here cascade across the entire ecosystem automatically. The four major US aggregators are Data Axle, Localeze (Neustar), Foursquare (as a data provider), and Acxiom. In the UK, Yell and Thomson Local serve similar aggregator roles.</p>

        <h3>Tier 2 — Core general directories</h3>
        <p>High-traffic, high-authority platforms that Google's local algorithm actively references: Google Business Profile (primary), Apple Maps, Bing Places, Yelp, Facebook Business, Yellow Pages, MapQuest, and TripAdvisor (for hospitality).</p>

        <h3>Tier 3 — Niche and local directories</h3>
        <p>Industry-specific and location-specific directories add depth and relevance signals: Healthgrades, Avvo, Houzz, Angi, HomeAdvisor, local chamber of commerce directories, city government business listings, and niche association member directories relevant to your vertical.</p>

        <h2 id="building-citations">How to build structured citations effectively</h2>
        <p>Citation building is more about accuracy and completeness than speed. A rushed submission campaign with inconsistent data does more harm than good. Follow this sequence:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Define your canonical NAP.</strong> Write down exactly how your business name, address, and phone should appear in every listing. Include suite/unit format, abbreviation decisions, and which phone number to use as primary.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit existing citations.</strong> Use BrightLocal Citation Tracker, Whitespark Citation Finder, or Moz Local to find every existing mention of your business. Export everything into a spreadsheet.</li>
          <li><strong>Fix before you build.</strong> Claim and correct all existing listings before adding new ones. Submitting to 50 new directories while leaving 30 existing ones incorrect is counterproductive.</li>
          <li><strong>Submit to tier-1 aggregators first.</strong> Corrections at the aggregator level propagate downstream, often fixing hundreds of derivative listings with a single submission.</li>
          <li><strong>Complete tier-2 general directories.</strong> Claim and fully optimise your Yelp, Apple Maps, Bing Places, Facebook, and Yellow Pages listings — including photos, categories, hours, and description.</li>
          <li><strong>Add tier-3 niche and local directories.</strong> Research the 10-20 most relevant niche directories for your industry and the top local directories in your city or region.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor quarterly.</strong> User-suggested edits, competitor sabotage, and data aggregator refreshes can corrupt your listings. Set a calendar reminder to audit the top 20 sources every 90 days.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="enriched-citations">Beyond NAP — enriched citations</h2>
        <p>Modern citation building goes beyond name, address, and phone. Fully enriched listings that include additional fields outperform sparse listings in local ranking studies and convert better with potential customers.</p>
        <p>Fields that add meaningful local ranking and conversion value:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Business categories</strong> — choosing the most precise primary category is the single highest-impact field after NAP</li>
          <li><strong>Business hours</strong> (including holiday hours)</li>
          <li><strong>Website URL</strong> — consistent with your canonical domain, with UTM if you want traffic attribution</li>
          <li><strong>Photos</strong> — exterior, interior, products, team</li>
          <li><strong>Description</strong> — keyword-relevant, unique per platform (not copy-pasted)</li>
          <li><strong>Payment methods</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Service area</strong> (for SABs)</li>
          <li><strong>Attributes</strong> — accessibility, LGBTQ-friendly, veteran-owned, etc.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Data point</div>
          <p>BrightLocal's Local Consumer Review Survey consistently shows that <strong>businesses with complete profiles</strong> (hours, photos, services listed) receive 7x more clicks than those with incomplete listings, independent of their ranking position.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices for structured citations in 2026</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>One phone number per location.</strong> Multi-location businesses often use tracking numbers — ensure the tracking number is consistent everywhere for that location.</li>
          <li><strong>Use your local number, not an 800 number.</strong> Local area codes are a proximity signal. National toll-free numbers dilute the local geo-relevance.</li>
          <li><strong>Address the physical storefront.</strong> For service-area businesses that don't want their address public, suppress it in GBP and leave it blank in directories rather than listing a P.O. box.</li>
          <li><strong>Match your GBP business name exactly.</strong> Your Google Business Profile is the reference point. All other directories should mirror your GBP name — no keyword stuffing, no taglines.</li>
          <li><strong>Track citation sources in a spreadsheet.</strong> Log every directory where you have a listing, the URL of the listing, and the login credentials used to claim it. This saves enormous time at audit time.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't build citations faster than you can monitor them.</strong> Scaling to 500 directories with no ongoing management creates a sprawling, unchecked NAP footprint that's hard to clean up.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common structured citation mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Inconsistent business name</strong> — using legal entity name in some places ("Acme Plumbing LLC") and trading name in others ("Acme Plumbing").</li>
          <li><strong>Multiple phone numbers</strong> — different listings showing different phone numbers for the same location.</li>
          <li><strong>Old address lingering</strong> — after moving, failing to update all directories, causing Google to see conflicting location signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Duplicate listings</strong> — multiple unclaimed listings on the same platform for the same location.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring data aggregators</strong> — building tier-2 and tier-3 listings while leaving incorrect aggregator data to continuously overwrite your corrections.</li>
          <li><strong>Neglecting niche directories</strong> — a dentist skipping Healthgrades and Zocdoc misses the sources Google trusts most for healthcare local intent.</li>
        </ul>

